# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multi-factor-authentication
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are the distinctive, measurable characteristics used to label and describe individuals.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are often categorized as physiological characteristics which are related to the shape of the body.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Examples include, but are not limited to fingerprint, palm veins, face recognition, DNA, palm print, hand geometry, iris recognition, retina, odor/scent, voice and shape of ears.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Behavioral characteristics are related to the pattern of behavior of a person, including but not limited to mouse movement, typing rhythm, gait, signature, voice, and behavioral profiling.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Some researchers have coined the term "**Behaviometrics"** (behavioral biometrics) to describe the latter class of biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] More traditional means of access control include token-based identification systems, such as a driver's license or passport, and knowledge-based identification systems, such as a password or personal identification number.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Since biometric identifiers are unique to individuals, they are more reliable in verifying identity than token and knowledge-based methods; however, the collection of biometric identifiers raises privacy concerns.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Many different aspects of human physiology, chemistry or behavior can be used for biometric authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The selection of a particular biometric for use in a specific application involves a weighting of several factors.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Jain *et al.* (1999) identified seven such factors to be used when assessing the suitability of any trait for use in biometric authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Biometric authentication is based upon biometric recognition which is an advanced method of recognizing biological and behavioral characteristics of an Individual.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Proper biometric use is very application dependent.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Certain biometrics will be better than others based on the required levels of convenience and security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] No single biometric will meet all the requirements of every possible application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The block diagram illustrates the two basic modes of a biometric system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] First, in verification (or authentication) mode the system performs a one-to-one comparison of a captured biometric with a specific template stored in a biometric database in order to verify the individual is the person they claim to be.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Three steps are involved in the verification of a person.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In the first step, reference models for all the users are generated and stored in the model database .
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In the second step, some samples are matched with reference models to generate the genuine and impostor scores and calculate the threshold.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This process may use a smart card, username, or ID number (e.g.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] PIN) to indicate which template should be used for comparison.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] *Positive recognition* is a common use of the verification mode, "where the aim is to prevent multiple people from using the same identity".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Second, in identification mode the system performs a one-to-many comparison against a biometric database in an attempt to establish the identity of an unknown individual.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The system will succeed in identifying the individual if the comparison of the biometric sample to a template in the database falls within a previously set threshold.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The latter function can only be achieved through biometrics since other methods of personal recognition, such as passwords, PINs, or keys, are ineffective.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The first time an individual uses a biometric system is called *enrollment*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] During enrollment, biometric information from an individual is captured and stored.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In subsequent uses, biometric information is detected and compared with the information stored at the time of enrollment.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Note that it is crucial that storage and retrieval of such systems themselves be secure if the biometric system is to be robust.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The first block (sensor) is the interface between the real world and the system; it has to acquire all the necessary data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Most of the time it is an image acquisition system, but it can change according to the characteristics desired.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The second block performs all the necessary pre-processing: it has to remove artifacts from the sensor, to enhance the input (e.g. removing background noise), to use some kind of normalization, etc.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In the third block, necessary features are extracted.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This step is an important step as the correct features need to be extracted in an optimal way.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] A vector of numbers or an image with particular properties is used to create a *template*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] A template is a synthesis of the relevant characteristics extracted from the source.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Elements of the biometric measurement that are not used in the comparison algorithm are discarded in the template to reduce the file size and to protect the identity of the enrollee.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] However, depending on the scope of the biometric system, original biometric image sources may be retained, such as the PIV-cards used in the Federal Information Processing Standard Personal Identity Verification (PIV) of Federal Employees and Contractors (FIPS 201).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] During the enrollment phase, the template is simply stored somewhere (on a card or within a database or both).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] During the matching phase, the obtained template is passed to a matcher that compares it with other existing templates, estimating the distance between them using any algorithm (e.g.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The matching program will analyze the template with the input.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This will then be output for a specified use or purpose (e.g. entrance in a restricted area), though it is a fear that the use of biometric data may face mission creep.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Selection of biometrics in any practical application depending upon the characteristic measurements and user requirements.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In selecting a particular biometric, factors to consider include, performance, social acceptability, ease of circumvention and/or spoofing, robustness, population coverage, size of equipment needed and identity theft deterrence.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The selection of a biometric is based on user requirements and considers sensor and device availability, computational time and reliability, cost, sensor size, and power consumption.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems use multiple sensors or biometrics to overcome the limitations of unimodal biometric systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] For instance iris recognition systems can be compromised by aging irises and electronic fingerprint recognition can be worsened by worn-out or cut fingerprints.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] While unimodal biometric systems are limited by the integrity of their identifier, it is unlikely that several unimodal systems will suffer from identical limitations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can obtain sets of information from the same marker (i.e., multiple images of an iris, or scans of the same finger) or information from different biometrics (requiring fingerprint scans and, using voice recognition, a spoken passcode).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can fuse these unimodal systems sequentially, simultaneously, a combination thereof, or in series, which refer to sequential, parallel, hierarchical and serial integration modes, respectively.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Fusion of the biometrics information can occur at different stages of a recognition system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In case of feature level fusion, the data itself or the features extracted from multiple biometrics are fused.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Matching-score level fusion consolidates the scores generated by multiple classifiers pertaining to different modalities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Finally, in case of decision level fusion the final results of multiple classifiers are combined via techniques such as majority voting.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Feature level fusion is believed to be more effective than the other levels of fusion because the feature set contains richer information about the input biometric data than the matching score or the output decision of a classifier.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Therefore, fusion at the feature level is expected to provide better recognition results.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Spoof attacks consist in submitting fake biometric traits to biometric systems, and are a major threat that can curtail their security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Multi-modal biometric systems are commonly believed to be intrinsically more robust to spoof attacks, but recent studies have shown that they can be evaded by spoofing even a single biometric trait.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The Fingerprint Involves minutiae extraction (terminations and bifurcations) and matching techniques.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Steps include image enhancement, binarization, ROI extraction, and minutiae thinning.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The Face system uses class-based scatter matrices to calculate features for recognition, and the Palm Vein acts as an unbreakable cryptographic key, ensuring only the correct user can access the system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The cancelable Biometrics concept allows biometric traits to be altered slightly to ensure privacy and avoid theft.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If compromised, new variations of biometric data can be issued.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The Encryption fingerprint template is encrypted using the palm vein key via XOR operations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This encrypted Fingerprint is hidden within the face image using steganographic techniques.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Enrollment and Verification for the Biometric data (Fingerprint, palm vein, face) are captured, encrypted, and embedded into a face image.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The system extracts the biometric data and compares it with stored values for Verification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The system was tested with fingerprint databases, achieving 75% verification accuracy at an equal error rate of 25% and processing time approximately 50 seconds for enrollment and 22 seconds for Verification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] High security due to palm vein encryption, effective against biometric spoofing, and the multimodal approach ensures reliability if one biometric fails.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Potential for integration with smart cards or on-card systems, enhancing security in personal identification systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The discriminating powers of all biometric technologies depend on the amount of entropy they are able to encode and use in matching.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] An early cataloguing of fingerprints dates back to 1885 when Juan Vucetich started a collection of fingerprints of criminals in Argentina.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Josh Ellenbogen and Nitzan Lebovic argued that Biometrics originated in the identification systems of criminal activity developed by Alphonse Bertillon (1853–1914) and by Francis Galton's theory of fingerprints and physiognomy.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Historian Keith Breckenridge note that Galton's travels in South Africa reinforced his early racial prejudices and inspired his later commitment to classifying human difference scientifically.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] According to Lebovic, Galton's work "led to the application of mathematical models to fingerprints, phrenology, and facial characteristics", as part of "absolute identification" and "a key to both inclusion and exclusion" of populations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Accordingly, "the biometric system is the absolute political weapon of our era" and a form of "soft control".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The theoretician David Lyon showed that during the past two decades biometric systems have penetrated the civilian market, and blurred the lines between governmental forms of control and private corporate control.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Adaptive biometric systems aim to auto-update the templates or model to the intra-class variation of the operational data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The two-fold advantages of these systems are solving the problem of limited training data and tracking the temporal variations of the input data through adaptation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Recently, adaptive biometrics have received a significant attention from the research community.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This research direction is expected to gain momentum because of their key promulgated advantages.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] First, with an adaptive biometric system, one no longer needs to collect a large number of biometric samples during the enrollment process.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Second, it is no longer necessary to enroll again or retrain the system from scratch in order to cope with the changing environment.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This convenience can significantly reduce the cost of maintaining a biometric system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Despite these advantages, there are several open issues involved with these systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] For mis-classification error (false acceptance) by the biometric system, cause adaptation using impostor sample.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] However, continuous research efforts are directed to resolve the open issues associated to the field of adaptive biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In recent times, biometrics based on brain (electroencephalogram) and heart (electrocardiogram) signals have emerged.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] An example is finger vein recognition, using pattern-recognition techniques, based on images of human vascular patterns.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The advantage of this newer technology is that it is more fraud resistant compared to conventional biometrics like fingerprints.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] However, such technology is generally more cumbersome and still has issues such as lower accuracy and poor reproducibility over time.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] On the portability side of biometric products, more and more vendors are embracing significantly miniaturized biometric authentication systems (BAS) thereby driving elaborate cost savings, especially for large-scale deployments.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] An operator signature is a biometric mode where the manner in which a person using a device or complex system is recorded as a verification template.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] One potential use for this type of biometric signature is to distinguish among remote users of telerobotic surgery systems that utilize public networks for communication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] John Michael (Mike) McConnell, a former vice admiral in the United States Navy, a former director of U.S.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] National Intelligence, and senior vice president of Booz Allen Hamilton, promoted the development of a future capability to require biometric authentication to access certain public networks in his keynote speech at the 2009 Biometric Consortium Conference.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] A basic premise in the above proposal is that the person that has uniquely authenticated themselves using biometrics with the computer is in fact also the agent performing potentially malicious actions from that computer.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] However, if control of the computer has been subverted, for example in which the computer is part of a botnet controlled by a hacker, then knowledge of the identity of the user at the terminal does not materially improve network security or aid law enforcement activities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Rather than tags or tattoos, biometric techniques may be used to identify individual animals: zebra stripes, blood vessel patterns in rodent ears, muzzle prints, bat wing patterns, primate facial recognition and koala spots have all been tried.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Biometrics have been considered also instrumental to the development of state authority (to put it in Foucauldian terms, of discipline and biopower).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] By turning the human subject into a collection of biometric parameters, biometrics would dehumanize the person, infringe bodily integrity, and, ultimately, offend human dignity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In a well-known case, Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben refused to enter the United States in protest at the United States Visitor and Immigrant Status Indicator (US-VISIT) program's requirement for visitors to be fingerprinted and photographed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Agamben argued that gathering of biometric data is a form of bio-political tattooing, akin to the tattooing of Jews during the Holocaust.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] According to Agamben, biometrics turn the human persona into a bare body.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Agamben refers to the two words used by Ancient Greeks for indicating "life", *zoe*, which is the life common to animals and humans, just life; and *bios*, which is life in the human context, with meanings and purposes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Agamben envisages the reduction to bare bodies for the whole humanity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] For him, a new bio-political relationship between citizens and the state is turning citizens into pure biological life (*zoe*) depriving them from their humanity (*bios*); and biometrics would herald this new world.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The stark expansion of biometric technologies in both the public and private sector magnifies this concern.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The increasing commodification of biometrics by the private sector adds to this danger of loss of human value.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Indeed, corporations value the biometric characteristics more than the individuals value them.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Other scholars have emphasized, however, that the globalized world is confronted with a huge mass of people with weak or absent civil identities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Most developing countries have weak and unreliable documents and the poorer people in these countries do not have even those unreliable documents.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Without certified personal identities, there is no certainty of right, no civil liberty.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] One can claim his rights, including the right to refuse to be identified, only if he is an identifiable subject, if he has a public identity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In such a sense, biometrics could play a pivotal role in supporting and promoting respect for human dignity and fundamental rights.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] It is possible that data obtained during biometric enrollment may be used in ways for which the enrolled individual has not consented.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Moreover, second generation biometrics, notably behavioral and electro-physiologic biometrics (e.g., based on electrocardiography, electroencephalography, electromyography), could be also used for emotion detection.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Unintended application scope: The authentication process correctly identifies the subject when the subject did not wish to be identified.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Covert identification: The subject is identified without seeking identification or authentication, i.e. a subject's face is identified in a crowd.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In terms of recognition or identification performance for a given trait, a biometric system should not exhibit accuracy differences across demographic groups.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Disparities in accuracy can lead to uneven error rates for populations defined by gender, race, age, or other attributes .
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Therefore, biometric systems should be designed and evaluated to ensure demographic fairness, providing equitable performance for all users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] When thieves cannot get access to secure properties, there is a chance that the thieves will stalk and assault the property owner to gain access.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If the item is secured with a biometric device, the damage to the owner could be irreversible, and potentially cost more than the secured property.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] For example, in 2005, Malaysian car thieves cut off a man's finger when attempting to steal his Mercedes-Benz S-Class.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In the context of biometric systems, presentation attacks may also be called "spoofing attacks".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] As per the recent ISO/IEC 30107 standard, presentation attacks are defined as "presentation to the biometric capture subsystem with the goal of interfering with the operation of the biometric system".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] These attacks can be either impersonation or obfuscation attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Impersonation attacks try to gain access by pretending to be someone else.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Obfuscation attacks may, for example, try to evade face detection and face recognition systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Several methods have been proposed to counteract presentation attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Biometrics are employed by many aid programs in times of crisis in order to prevent fraud and ensure that resources are properly available to those in need.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Humanitarian efforts are motivated by promoting the welfare of individuals in need, however the use of biometrics as a form of surveillance humanitarianism can create conflict due to varying interests of the groups involved in the particular situation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Disputes over the use of biometrics between aid programs and party officials stalls the distribution of resources to people that need help the most.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In July 2019, the United Nations World Food Program and Houthi Rebels were involved in a large dispute over the use of biometrics to ensure resources are provided to the hundreds of thousands of civilians in Yemen whose lives are threatened.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The refusal to cooperate with the interests of the United Nations World Food Program resulted in the suspension of food aid to the Yemen population.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The use of biometrics may provide aid programs with valuable information, however its potential solutions may not be best suited for chaotic times of crisis.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Conflicts that are caused by deep-rooted political problems, in which the implementation of biometrics may not provide a long-term solution.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] One advantage of passwords over biometrics is that they can be re-issued.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If a token or a password is lost or stolen, it can be cancelled and replaced by a newer version.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This is not naturally available in biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If someone's face is compromised from a database, they cannot cancel or reissue it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If the electronic biometric identifier is stolen, it is nearly impossible to change a biometric feature.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This renders the person's biometric feature questionable for future use in authentication, such as the case with the hacking of security-clearance-related background information from the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) in the United States.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Cancelable biometrics is a way in which to incorporate protection and the replacement features into biometrics to create a more secure system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] "Cancelable biometrics refers to the intentional and systematically repeatable distortion of biometric features in order to protect sensitive user-specific data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] If a cancelable feature is compromised, the distortion characteristics are changed, and the same biometrics is mapped to a new template, which is used subsequently.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Several methods for generating new exclusive biometrics have been proposed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The first fingerprint-based cancelable biometric system was designed and developed by Tulyakov *et al.* Essentially, cancelable biometrics perform a distortion of the biometric image or features before matching.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The variability in the distortion parameters provides the cancelable nature of the scheme.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Soft biometrics are understood as **not strict biometrical** recognition practices that are proposed in favour of identity cheaters and stealers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Traits are physical, behavioral or adhered human characteristics that have been derived from the way human beings normally distinguish their peers (e.g. height, gender, hair color).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] They are used to complement the identity information provided by the primary biometric identifiers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Although soft biometric characteristics lack the distinctiveness and permanence to recognize an individual uniquely and reliably, and can be easily faked, they provide some evidence about the users identity that could be beneficial.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In other words, despite the fact they are unable to individualize a subject, they are effective in distinguishing between people.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Combinations of personal attributes like gender, race, eye color, height and other visible identification marks can be used to improve the performance of traditional biometric systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Most soft biometrics can be easily collected and are actually collected during enrollment.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Two main ethical issues are raised by soft biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Second, soft biometrics have strong potential for categorizing and profiling people, so risking of supporting processes of stigmatization and exclusion.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Many countries, including the United States, are planning to share biometric data with other nations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] According to an article written in 2009 by S.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Magnuson in the National Defense Magazine entitled "Defense Department Under Pressure to Share Biometric Data" the United States has bilateral agreements with other nations aimed at sharing biometric data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Certain members of the civilian community are worried about how biometric data is used but full disclosure may not be forthcoming.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] This also potentially applies to Biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] It goes on to say that this is a classic feature of intelligence and military operations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] In short, the goal is to preserve the security of 'sources and methods'.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The frequent use of biometric authentication for security and the permanence of an individuals biometrics make the security of biometric data crucial.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The United States does not have a nationwide data privacy law that includes biometrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Several states and local governments, led by the Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act, have legislation regarding biometric data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The FTC has also taken actions to protect biometric data including against Facebook in 2019, charging they misrepresented their uses of facial recognition technology.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] Among low to middle income countries, roughly 1.2 billion people have already received identification through a biometric identification program.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] There are also numerous countries applying biometrics for voter registration and similar electoral purposes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] India's national ID program called Aadhaar is the largest biometric database in the world.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] It is a biometrics-based digital identity assigned for a person's lifetime, verifiable online instantly in the public domain, at any time, from anywhere, in a paperless way.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] It is designed to enable government agencies to deliver a retail public service, securely based on biometric data (fingerprint, iris scan and face photo), along with demographic data (name, age, gender, address, parent/spouse name, mobile phone number) of a person.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] The data is transmitted in encrypted form over the internet for authentication, aiming to free it from the limitations of physical presence of a person at a given place.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] About 550 million residents have been enrolled and assigned 480 million Aadhaar national identification numbers as of 7 November 2013.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] It aims to cover the entire population of 1.2 billion in a few years.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] However, it is being challenged by critics over privacy concerns and possible transformation of the state into a surveillance state, or into a Banana republic.§ The project was also met with mistrust regarding the safety of the social protection infrastructures.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] To tackle the fear amongst the people, India's supreme court put a new ruling into action that stated that privacy from then on was seen as a fundamental right.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/biometrics] On 24 August 2017 this new law was established.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] HOTP was published as an informational IETF RFC 4226 in December 2005, documenting the algorithm along with a Java implementation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Since then, the algorithm has been adopted by many companies worldwide (see below).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The HOTP algorithm is a freely available open standard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The HOTP algorithm provides a method of authentication by symmetric generation of human-readable passwords, or *values*, each used for only one authentication attempt.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The one-time property leads directly from the single use of each counter value.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Both parties compute the HOTP value derived from the secret key *K* and the counter *C*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Then the authenticator checks its locally generated value against the value supplied by the authenticated.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The authenticator and the authenticated entity increment the counter *C* independently.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Since the authenticated entity may increment the counter more than the authenticator, RFC 4226 recommends a resynchronization protocol.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] It proposes that the authenticator repeatedly try verification ahead of their counter through a window of size *s*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The authenticator's counter continues forward of the value at which verification succeeds, and requires no actions by the authenticated entity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] To protect against brute-force attacks targeting the small size of HOTP values, the RFC also recommends implementing persistent throttling of HOTP verification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] This can be achieved by either locking out verification after a small number of failed attempts, or by linearly increasing the delay after each failed attempt.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] 6-digit codes are commonly provided by proprietary hardware tokens from a number of vendors informing the default value of *d*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Truncation extracts 31 bits or ${\textstyle \log _{10}(2^{31})\approx 9.3}$ decimal digits, meaning that *d* can be at most 10, with the 10th digit adding less variation, taking values of 0, 1, and 2 (i.e., 0.3 digits).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] After verification, the authenticator can authenticate itself simply by generating the next HOTP value, returning it, and then the authenticated can generate their own HOTP value to verify it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Note that counters are guaranteed to be synchronised at this point in the process.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] That is, the value is the *d* least significant base-10 digits of HOTP.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] where the counter *C* must be used big-endian.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] where ":" is used to extract bits from a starting bit number up to and including an ending bit number, where these bit numbers are 0-origin.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The use of "19" in the above formula relates to the size of the output from the hash function.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] With the default of SHA-1, the output is 20 bytes, and so the last byte is byte 19 (0-origin).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] 31 bits are a single bit short of a 4-byte word.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Thus the value can be placed inside such a word without using the sign bit (the most significant bit).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] This is done to definitely avoid doing modular arithmetic on negative numbers, as this has many differing definitions and implementations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The following Python code implements the HMAC-SHA1 and HOTP algorithms.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Some implementations of HOTP and TOTP for smartphones allow users to scan QR codes to add HOTP and TOTP tokens to their authenticator apps.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] These QR codes contain Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) with the scheme `otpauth://`.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] HOTP `otpauth://` URIs begin with `otpauth://hotp/` and must contain a label, secret, and counter.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The label is encoded as part of the path, while the secret and counter are encoded as query parameters.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The URI may optionally contain other fields, such as the number of digits (which defaults to 6), the algorithm used (which defaults to SHA1), and the issuer name.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] The secret is encoded as RFC 4648 Base32, with padding omitted.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] For example, the URI `otpauth://hotp/Wikipedian?secret=JBSWY3DPFQQHO33SNRSCC&counter=42` represents a HOTP token labeled "Wikipedian", with the secret `Hello, world!` encoded as ASCII, and the initial counter 42.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] When added to an authenticator, it should produce the code `439256`.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Both hardware and software tokens are available from various vendors, for some of them see references below.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Software tokens are available for (nearly) all major mobile/smartphone platforms (J2ME, Android, iPhone, BlackBerry, Maemo, macOS, and Windows Mobile).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/hmac-based-one-time-password] Although the early reception from some of the computer press was negative during 2004 and 2005, after IETF adopted HOTP as RFC 4226 in December 2005, various vendors started to produce HOTP-compatible tokens and/or whole authentication solutions.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Usage of MFA has increased in recent years.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Security issues which can cause the bypass of MFA are fatigue attacks, phishing and SIM swapping.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Accounts with MFA enabled are significantly less likely to be compromised.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Authentication takes place when someone tries to log into a computer resource (such as a computer network, device, or application).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The resource requires the user to supply the identity by which the user is known to the resource, along with evidence of the authenticity of the user's claim to that identity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Simple authentication requires only one such piece of evidence (factor), typically a password, or occasionally multiple pieces of evidence all of the same type, as with a credit card number and a card verification code (CVC).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] For additional security, the resource may require more than one factor—multi-factor authentication, or two-factor authentication in cases where exactly two types of evidence are to be supplied.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The use of multiple authentication factors to prove one's identity is based on the premise that an unauthorized actor is unlikely to be able to supply all of the factors required for access.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] If, in an authentication attempt, at least one of the components is missing or supplied incorrectly, the user's identity is not established with sufficient certainty and access to the asset (e.g., a building, or data) being protected by multi-factor authentication then remains blocked.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] An example of two-factor authentication is the withdrawing of money from an ATM; only the correct combination of a physically present bank card (something the user possesses) and a PIN (something the user knows) allows the transaction to be carried out.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Two other examples are to supplement a user-controlled password with a one-time password (OTP) or code generated or received by an authenticator (e.g. a security token or smartphone) that only the user possesses.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] An authenticator app enables two-factor authentication in a different way, by showing a randomly generated and constantly refreshing code, rather than sending an SMS or using another method.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This code is a Time-based one-time password (a *TOTP*), and the authenticator app contains the key material that allows the generation of these codes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Knowledge factors ("something only the user knows") are a form of authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In this form, the user is required to prove knowledge of a secret in order to authenticate.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] A password is a secret word or string of characters that is used for user authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This is the most commonly used mechanism of authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication techniques rely on passwords as one factor of authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Variations include both longer ones formed from multiple words (a passphrase) and the shorter, purely numeric, PIN commonly used for ATM access.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Traditionally, passwords are expected to be memorized, but can also be written down on a hidden paper or text file.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Possession factors ("something only the user has") have been used for authentication for centuries, in the form of a key to a lock.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The basic principle is that the key embodies a secret that is shared between the lock and the key, and the same principle underlies possession factor authentication in computer systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] A security token is an example of a possession factor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] *soft token*) is a type of two-factor authentication security device that may be used to authorize the use of computer services.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] A soft token may not be a device the user interacts with.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Typically an X.509v3 certificate is loaded onto the device and stored securely to serve this purpose.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Inherent factors ("something the user is"), are factors associated with the user, and are usually biometric methods, including fingerprint, face, voice, or iris recognition.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Behavioral biometrics such as keystroke dynamics can also be used.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Increasingly, a fourth factor is coming into play involving the physical location of the user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] While hard wired to the corporate network, a user could be allowed to login using only a pin code, whereas if the user was working remotely, a more secure MFA method such as entering a code from a soft token as well could be required.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Adapting the type of MFA method and frequency to a users' location will enable the avoidance of risks common to remote working.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Systems for network admission control work in similar ways where the level of network access can be contingent on the specific network a device is connected to, such as Wi-Fi vs wired connectivity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This also allows a user to move between offices and dynamically receive the same level of network access in each.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Two-factor authentication over text message was developed as early as 1996, when AT&T described a system for authorizing transactions based on an exchange of codes over two-way pagers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication vendors offer mobile phone-based authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Some methods include push-based authentication, QR code-based authentication, one-time password authentication (event-based and time-based), and SMS-based verification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] SMS-based verification suffers from some security concerns.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Phones can be cloned, apps can run on several phones and cell-phone maintenance personnel can read SMS texts.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Not least, cell phones can be compromised in general, meaning the phone is no longer something only the user has.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The major drawback of authentication including something the user possesses is that the user must carry around the physical token (the USB stick, the bank card, the key or similar), practically at all times.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Many organizations forbid carrying USB and electronic devices in or out of premises owing to malware and data theft risks, and most important machines do not have USB ports for the same reason.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Physical tokens usually do not scale, typically requiring a new token for each new account and system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Procuring and subsequently replacing tokens of this kind involves costs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In addition, there are inherent conflicts and unavoidable trade-offs between usability and security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Two-step authentication involving mobile phones and smartphones provides an alternative to dedicated physical devices.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] To authenticate, people can use their personal access codes to the device (i.e. something that only the individual user knows) plus a one-time-valid, dynamic passcode, typically consisting of 4 to 6 digits.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The passcode can be sent to their mobile device by SMS or can be generated by a one-time passcode-generator app.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In both cases, the advantage of using a mobile phone is that there is no need for an additional dedicated token, as users tend to carry their mobile devices around at all times.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Notwithstanding the popularity of SMS verification, security advocates have publicly criticized SMS verification, and in July 2016, a United States NIST draft guideline proposed deprecating it as a form of authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] A year later NIST reinstated SMS verification as a valid authentication channel in the finalized guideline.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] As early as 2011, Duo Security was offering push notifications for MFA via a mobile app.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In 2016 and 2017 respectively, both Google and Apple started offering user two-step authentication with push notifications as an alternative method.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Security of SMS-delivered security tokens fully depends on the mobile operator's operational security and can be easily breached by wiretapping or SIM cloning by national security agencies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard, requirement 8.3, requires the use of MFA for all remote network access that originates from outside the network to a Card Data Environment (CDE).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Beginning with PCI-DSS version 3.2, the use of MFA is required for all administrative access to the CDE, even if the user is within a trusted network.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The second Payment Services Directive requires "strong customer authentication" on most electronic payments in the European Economic Area since September 14, 2019.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In India, the Reserve Bank of India mandated two-factor authentication for all online transactions made using a debit or credit card using either a password or a one-time password sent over SMS.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This requirement was removed in 2016 for transactions up to ₹2,000 after opting-in with the issuing bank.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Vendors such as Uber have been mandated by the bank to amend their payment processing systems in compliance with this two-factor authentication rollout.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Details for authentication for federal employees and contractors in the U.S. are defined in Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] IT regulatory standards for access to federal government systems require the use of multi-factor authentication to access sensitive IT resources, for example when logging on to network devices to perform administrative tasks and when accessing any computer using a privileged login.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] NIST Special Publication 800-63-3 discusses various forms of two-factor authentication and provides guidance on using them in business processes requiring different levels of assurance.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In response to the publication, numerous authentication vendors began improperly promoting challenge-questions, secret images, and other knowledge-based methods as "multi-factor" authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Considering the reliability of the method, in some countries, MFA is obligatory in certain industries, such as healthcare, to prevent the theft of sensitive information.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule has historically listed access controls as a required implementation specification but did not explicitly mandate multi-factor authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The HHS Office for Civil Rights noted in enforcement guidance that the lack of MFA was a contributing factor in multiple healthcare data breaches investigated under HIPAA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In December 2024, HHS published a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking that would make multi-factor authentication a mandatory requirement for all HIPAA-regulated entities accessing electronic protected health information.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] According to proponents, multi-factor authentication could drastically reduce the incidence of online identity theft and other online fraud, because the victim's password would no longer be enough to give a thief permanent access to their information.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] However, many multi-factor authentication approaches remain vulnerable to phishing, man-in-the-browser, and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] To counter phishing attacks, users should not share their verification codes with anyone, and many web application providers will place an advisory in an e-mail or SMS containing a code.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that cybercriminals had exploited SS7 vulnerabilities to bypass SMS based two-step authentication to do unauthorized withdrawals from users' bank accounts.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] The criminals first infected the account holder's computers in an attempt to steal their bank account credentials and phone numbers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Then the attackers purchased access to a fake telecom provider and set up a redirect for the victim's phone number to a handset controlled by them.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Finally, the attackers logged into victims' online bank accounts and requested for the money on the accounts to be withdrawn to accounts owned by the criminals.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] SMS passcodes were routed to phone numbers controlled by the attackers and the criminals transferred the money out.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] An increasingly common approach to defeating MFA is to bombard the user with many requests to accept a log-in, until the user eventually succumbs to the volume of requests and by mistake accepts one.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This form of social engineering is called *multi-factor authentication fatigue attack* (also MFA fatigue attack or MFA bombing), and may include other elements, such as calls pretending to be from IT support.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] When MFA applications are configured to send push notifications to end users, an attacker can send a flood of login attempts in the hope that a user will click on accept at least once.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In 2022, Microsoft deployed a mitigation against MFA fatigue attacks with their authenticator app, by optionally requiring the user to type in a number in addition to clicking "approve".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In September 2022 Uber security was breached by a member of Lapsus$ using a multi-factor fatigue attack.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In early 2024, a small percentage of Apple consumers experienced a MFA fatigue attack that was caused by a hacker that bypassed the rate limit and Captcha on Apple’s “Forgot Password” page.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication products require users to deploy client software to make multi-factor authentication systems work.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Some vendors have created separate installation packages for network login, Web access credentials, and VPN connection credentials.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] For such products, there may be four or five different software packages to push down to the client PC in order to make use of the token or smart card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] This translates to four or five packages on which version control has to be performed, and four or five packages to check for conflicts with business applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] If access can be operated using web pages, it is possible to limit the overheads outlined above to a single application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] With other multi-factor authentication technology such as hardware token products, no software must be installed by end-users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Some studies have shown that poorly implemented MFA recovery procedures can introduce new vulnerabilities that attackers may exploit.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] There are drawbacks to multi-factor authentication that are keeping many approaches from becoming widespread.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Some users have difficulty keeping track of a hardware token or USB plug.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Many users do not have the technical skills needed to install a client-side software certificate by themselves.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Generally, multi-factor solutions require additional investment for implementation and costs for maintenance.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Most hardware token-based systems are proprietary, and some vendors charge an annual fee per user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Deployment of hardware tokens is logistically challenging.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Hardware tokens may get damaged or lost, and issuance of tokens in large industries such as banking or even within large enterprises needs to be managed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In addition to deployment costs, multi-factor authentication often carries significant additional support costs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] A 2008 survey of over 120 U.S. credit unions by the *Credit Union Journal* reported on the support costs associated with two-factor authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In their report, software certificates and software toolbar approaches were reported to have the highest support costs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] Research into deployments of multi-factor authentication schemes has shown that one of the elements that tend to impact the adoption of such systems is the line of business of the organization that deploys the multi-factor authentication system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] While the perception is that multi-factor authentication is within the realm of perfect security, Roger Grimes writes that if not properly implemented and configured, multi-factor authentication can in fact be easily defeated.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] In 2013, Kim Dotcom claimed to have invented two-factor authentication in a 2000 patent, and briefly threatened to sue all the major web services.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multi-factor-authentication] However, the European Patent Office revoked his patent in light of an earlier 1998 U.S. patent held by AT&T.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Multifactor Authentication (MFA) or Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) is when a user is required to present more than one type of evidence in order to authenticate on a system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] There are five different types of evidence (or factors) and any combination of these can be used, however in practice only the first three are common in web applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] It should be noted that requiring multiple instances of the same authentication factor (such as needing both a password and a PIN) **does not constitute MFA** and offers minimal additional security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The factors used should be independent of each other and should not be able to be compromised by the same attack.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] While the following sections discuss the disadvantage and weaknesses of various different types of MFA, in many cases these are only relevant against targeted attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common way that user accounts get compromised on applications is through weak, re-used or stolen passwords.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Despite any technical security controls implemented on the application, users are liable to choose weak passwords, or to use the same password on different applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] As developers or system administrators, it should be assumed that users' passwords will be compromised at some point, and the system should be designed in order to defend against this.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] MFA is by far the best defense against the majority of password-related attacks, including brute-force, credential stuffing and password spraying, with analysis by Microsoft suggesting that it would have stopped 99.9% of account compromises.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The biggest disadvantage of MFA is the increase in management complexity for both administrators and end users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Many less technical users may find it difficult to configure and use MFA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Exactly when and how MFA is implemented in an application will vary on a number of different factors, including the threat model of the application, the technical level of the users, and the level of administrative control over the users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] These need to be considered on a per-application basis.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, the following recommendations are generally appropriate for most applications, and provide an initial starting point to consider.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] MFA is a critical security control, and is recommended for all applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The following sections provide guidance on how to implement MFA, and the considerations that should be taken into account.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Many industries and countries have regulations that require the use of MFA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is particularly common in the finance and healthcare sectors, and is often required in order to comply with the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) in the European Union.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] It is important to consider these requirements when implementing MFA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most important place to require MFA on an application is when the user logs in.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] If the application provides multiple ways for a user to authenticate these should all require MFA, or have other protections implemented.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] A common area that is missed is if the application provides a separate API that can be used to login, or has an associated mobile application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] OTPs are authentication secrets and should be handled with password-like hygiene.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] While their security traits differ from long-lived passwords, improper handling can still lead to user account compromise.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Hashing OTPs is still recommended, but for different reasons than password hashing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] OTPs typically have a very small keyspace (for example, ~1 million possibilities for a 6-digit code), which means a database attacker can brute-force any OTP hash quickly.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] As a result, hashing OTPs does not provide strong offline attack resistance in the way password hashing does.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The goal is short-term exposure protection, not long-term cryptographic secrecy.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Having to frequently login with MFA creates an additional burden for users, and may cause them to disable MFA on the application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Risk based authentication can be used to reduce the frequency of MFA prompts, by only requiring MFA when the user is performing an action that is considered to be high risk.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Passkeys based on the FIDO2 standard are a new form of MFA that combines characteristics of possession-based and either knowledge-based or inherence-based authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The user is required to have a physical device (such as a mobile phone) and to enter a PIN or use biometric authentication in order to authenticate.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The user's device then generates a cryptographic key that is used to authenticate with the server.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is a very secure form of MFA and is resistant to phishing attacks while also being frictionless for the user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] One of the biggest challenges with implementing MFA is handling users who forget or lose their additional factors.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] In order to prevent users from being locked out of the application, there needs to be a mechanism for them to regain access to their account if they can't use their existing MFA; however it is also crucial that this doesn't provide an attacker with a way to bypass MFA and hijack their account.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] There is no definitive "best way" to do this, and what is appropriate will vary hugely based on the security of the application, and also the level of control over the users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Solutions that work for a corporate application where all the staff know each other are unlikely to be feasible for a publicly available application with thousands of users all over the world.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Every recovery method has its own advantages and disadvantages, and these need to be evaluated in the context of the application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Users may need to update their authentication factors, such as changing a phone number, migrating to a new authenticator app, or replacing a lost hardware token.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Because attackers can exploit this process to take over accounts, it must be strictly secured.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This ensures that even if a session is compromised, attackers cannot silently replace the user’s MFA factors and lock the legitimate user out.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] There are a number of third party services that provide MFA as a service.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] These can be a good option for applications that don't have the resources to implement MFA themselves, or for applications that require a high level of assurance in their MFA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, it is important to consider the security of the third party service, and the implications of using it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] For example, if the third party service is compromised, it could allow an attacker to bypass MFA on all of the applications that use it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Knowledge-based, the most common type of authentication is based on something the users knows - typically a password.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The biggest advantage of this factor is that it has very low requirements for both the developers and the end user, as it does not require any special hardware, or integration with other services.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Passwords and PINs are the most common form of authentication due to the simplicity of implementing them.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The Authentication Cheat Sheet has guidance on how to implement a strong password policy, and the Password Storage Cheat Sheet has guidance on how to securely store passwords.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Most multifactor authentication systems make use of a password, as well as at least one other factor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Possession-based authentication is based on the user having a physical or digital item that is required to authenticate.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is the most common form of MFA, and is often used in conjunction with passwords.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common types of possession-based authentication are hardware and software tokens, and digital certificates.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] If properly implemented then this can be significantly more difficult for a remote attacker to compromise; however it also creates an additional administrative burden on the user, as they must keep the authentication factor with them whenever they wish to use it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] One-Time Password (OTP) tokens are a form of possession-based authentication, where the user is required to submit a constantly changing numeric code in order to authenticate.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common of which is Time-based One-Time Password (TOTP) tokens, which can be both hardware and software based.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Hardware OTP Tokens generate a constantly changing numeric codes, which must be submitted when authenticating.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Most well-known of these is the RSA SecureID, which generates a six digit number that changes every 60 seconds.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] A cheaper and easier alternative to hardware tokens is using software to generate Time-based One-Time Password (TOTP) codes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This would typically involve the user installing a TOTP application on their mobile phone, and then scanning a QR code provided by the web application which provides the initial seed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The authenticator app then generates a six digit number every 60 seconds, in much the same way as a hardware token.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Most websites use standardized TOTP tokens, allowing the user to install any authenticator app that supports TOTP.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, a small number of applications use their own variants of this (such as Symantec), which requires the users to install a specific app in order to use the service.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This should be avoided in favour of a standards-based approach.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Universal Second Factor (U2F) is a standard for USB/NFC hardware tokens that implement challenge-response based authentication, rather than requiring the user to manually enter the code.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This would typically be done by the user pressing a button on the token, or tapping it against their NFC reader.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common U2F token is the YubiKey.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Digital certificates are files that are stored on the user's device which are automatically provided alongside the user's password when authenticating.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common type is X.509 certificates more commonly known as client certificates.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Certificates are supported by all major web browsers, and once installed require no further interaction from the user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The certificates should be linked to an individual's user account in order to prevent users from trying to authenticate against other accounts.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Smartcards are credit-card size cards with a chip containing a digital certificate for the user, which is unlocked with a PIN.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] They are commonly used for operating system authentication, but are rarely used in web applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] SMS messages or phone calls can be used to provide users with a single-use code that they must submit as an additional factor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Due to the risks posed by these methods, they should not be used to protect applications that hold Personally Identifiable Information (PII) or where there is financial risk. e.g. healthcare and banking.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] NIST SP 800-63B classifies these as restricted authenticators and discourages their use for applications containing PII.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Email verification requires that the user enters a code or clicks a link sent to their email address.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] There is some debate as to whether email constitutes a form of MFA, because if the user does not have MFA configured on their email account, it simply requires knowledge of the user's email password (which is often the same as their application password).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, it is included here for completeness.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Inherence-based authentication is based on the physical attributes of the user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is less common for web applications as it requires the user to have specific hardware, and is often considered to be the most invasive in terms of privacy.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, it is commonly used for operating system authentication, and is also used in some mobile applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Location-based authentication is based on the user's physical location.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] It is sometimes argued that location is used when deciding whether or not to require MFA (as discussed above) however this is effectively the same as considering it to be a factor in its own right.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Two prominent examples of this are the Conditional Access Policies available in Microsoft Azure, and the Network Unlock functionality in BitLocker.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] The source IP address the user is connecting from can be used as a factor, typically in an allow-list based approach.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This could either be based on a static list (such as corporate office ranges) or a dynamic list (such as previous IP addresses the user has authenticated from).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Rather than using the exact IP address of the user, the geographic location that the IP address is registered to can be used.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is less precise, but may be more feasible to implement in environments where IP addresses are not static.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] A common usage would be to require additional authentication factors when an authentication attempt is made from outside of the user's normal country.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Geofencing is a more precise version of geolocation, which allows the user to define a specific area in which they are allowed to authenticate.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is often used in mobile applications, where the user's location can be determined with a high degree of accuracy using geopositioning hardware like GPS.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Behavior-based authentication is based on the user's behavior, such as the way they type, move their mouse, or use their mobile device.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is the least common form of MFA and is combined with other factors to increase the level of assurance in the user's identity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] It is also the most difficult to implement and may require specific hardware along with a significant amount of data and processing power to analyze the user's behavior.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Behavioral profiling is based on the way the user interacts with the application, such as the time of day they log in, the devices they use, and the way they navigate the application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This is rapidly becoming more common in web applications when combined with Risk Based Authentication and User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Keystroke and mouse dynamics are based on the way the user types and moves their mouse.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] For example, the time between key presses, the time between key presses and releases, and the speed and acceleration of the mouse.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Largely theoretical, and not widely used in practice.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Gait analysis is based on the way the user walks using cameras and sensors.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] They are often used in physical security systems, but are not widely used in web applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Mobile device applications may be able to use the accelerometer to detect the user's gait and use this as an additional factor, however this is still largely theoretical.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] Adaptive (or Risk-Based) Authentication adjusts authentication requirements dynamically based on the context of the login attempt.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This technique helps improve user experience while strengthening security by applying additional verification steps only when risk is elevated.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] This method is widely used in modern authentication systems to balance usability and security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/multifactor-authentication-cheat-sheet] However, developers must ensure that risk signals cannot be spoofed and that fallback mechanisms are not weaker than the primary MFA methods.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] A **security token** is a peripheral device used to gain access to an electronically restricted resource.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The token is used in addition to, or in place of, a password.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Examples of security tokens include wireless key cards used to open locked doors, a banking token used as a digital authenticator for signing in to online banking, or signing transactions such as wire transfers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Security tokens can be used to store information such as passwords, cryptographic keys used to generate digital signatures, or biometric data (such as fingerprints).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Some designs incorporate tamper resistant packaging, while others may include small keypads to allow entry of a PIN or a simple button to start a generation routine with some display capability to show a generated key number.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Connected tokens utilize a variety of interfaces including USB, near-field communication (NFC), radio-frequency identification (RFID), or Bluetooth.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Some tokens have audio capabilities designed for those who are vision-impaired.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] All tokens contain some secret information used to prove identity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The device contains a password that is physically hidden (not visible to the possessor), but is transmitted for each authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The token and the authentication server must have synchronized clocks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] , it is possible to prove possession of a private key without revealing that key.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The authentication server encrypts a challenge (typically a random number, or at least data with some random parts) with a public key; the device proves it possesses a copy of the matching private key by providing the decrypted challenge.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Time-synchronized, one-time passwords change constantly at a set time interval; e.g., once per minute.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] To do this, some sort of synchronization must exist between the client's token and the authentication server.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] For disconnected tokens, this time-synchronization is done before the token is distributed to the client.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Other token types do the synchronization when the token is inserted into an input device.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The main problem with time-synchronized tokens is that they can, over time, become unsynchronized.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] However, some such systems, such as RSA's SecurID, allow the user to re-synchronize the server with the token, sometimes by entering several consecutive passcodes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Most also cannot have replaceable batteries and only last up to 5 years before having to be replaced – so there is an additional cost.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Another type of one-time password uses a complex mathematical algorithm, such as a hash chain, to generate a series of one-time passwords from a secret shared key.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Each password is unique, even when previous passwords are known.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The open-source OATH algorithm is standardized; other algorithms are covered by US patents.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Each password is observably unpredictable and independent of previous ones, whereby an adversary would be unable to guess what the next password may be, even with knowledge of all previous passwords.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Tokens can contain chips with functions varying from very simple to very complex, including multiple authentication methods.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The simplest security tokens do not need any connection to a computer.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The tokens have a physical display; the authenticating user simply enters the displayed number to log in.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Other tokens connect to the computer using wireless techniques, such as Bluetooth.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] These tokens transfer a key sequence to the local client or to a nearby access point.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Alternatively, another form of token that has been widely available for many years is a mobile device which communicates using an out-of-band channel (like voice, SMS, or USSD).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Still other tokens plug into the computer and may require a PIN.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Depending on the type of the token, the computer OS will then either read the key from the token and perform a cryptographic operation on it, or ask the token's firmware to perform this operation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] A related application is the hardware dongle required by some computer programs to prove ownership of the software.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The dongle is placed in an input device and the software accesses the I/O device in question to authorize the use of the software in question.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Commercial solutions are provided by a variety of vendors, each with their own proprietary (and often patented) implementation of variously used security features.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Token designs meeting certain security standards are certified in the United States as compliant with FIPS 140, a federal security standard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Disconnected tokens have neither a physical nor logical connection to the client computer.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] They typically do not require a special input device, and instead use a built-in screen to display the generated authentication data, which the user enters manually themselves via a keyboard or keypad.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Disconnected tokens are the most common type of security token used (usually in combination with a password) in two-factor authentication for online identification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Connected tokens are tokens that must be physically connected to the computer with which the user is authenticating.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Tokens in this category automatically transmit the authentication information to the client computer once a physical connection is made, eliminating the need for the user to manually enter the authentication information.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] However, in order to use a connected token, the appropriate input device must be installed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The most common types of physical tokens are smart cards and USB tokens (also called *security keys*), which require a smart card reader and a USB port respectively.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Increasingly, FIDO2 tokens, supported by the open specification group FIDO Alliance have become popular for consumers with mainstream browser support beginning in 2015 and supported by popular websites and social media sites.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Older PC card tokens are made to work primarily with laptops.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Type II PC Cards are preferred as a token as they are half as thick as Type III.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The audio jack port is a relatively practical method to establish connection between mobile devices, such as iPhone, iPad and Android, and other accessories.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The most well known device is called Square, a credit card reader for iOS and Android devices.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Some use a special purpose interface (e.g. the crypto ignition key deployed by the United States National Security Agency).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Tokens can also be used as a photo ID card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Cell phones and PDAs can also serve as security tokens with proper programming.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Many connected tokens use smart card technology.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Smart cards can be very cheap (around ten cents) and contain proven security mechanisms (as used by financial institutions, like cash cards).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] However, computational performance of smart cards is often rather limited because of extreme low power consumption and ultra-thin form-factor requirements.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Smart-card-based USB tokens which contain a smart card chip inside provide the functionality of both USB tokens and smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] They enable a broad range of security solutions and provide the abilities and security of a traditional smart card without requiring a unique input device.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] From the computer operating system's point of view such a token is a USB-connected smart card reader with one non-removable smart card present.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Unlike connected tokens, contactless tokens form a logical connection to the client computer but do not require a physical connection.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The absence of the need for physical contact makes them more convenient than both connected and disconnected tokens.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] As a result, contactless tokens are a popular choice for keyless entry systems and electronic payment solutions such as Mobil Speedpass, which uses RFID to transmit authentication info from a keychain token.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] However, there have been various security concerns raised about RFID tokens after researchers at Johns Hopkins University and RSA Laboratories discovered that RFID tags could be easily cracked and cloned.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Another downside is that contactless tokens have relatively short battery lives; usually only 5–6 years, which is low compared to USB tokens which may last more than 10 years.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Some tokens however do allow the batteries to be changed, thus reducing costs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The Bluetooth Low Energy protocols provide long lasting battery lifecycle of wireless transmission.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Although, the automatic transmission power control attempts for radial distance estimates.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The escape is available apart from the standardised Bluetooth power control algorithm to provide a calibration on minimally required transmission power.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Bluetooth tokens are often combined with a USB token, thus working in both a connected and a disconnected state.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Bluetooth authentication works when closer than 32 feet (9.8 meters).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] When the Bluetooth link is not properly operable, the token may be inserted into a USB input device to function.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Another combination is with a smart card to store locally larger amounts of identity data and process information as well.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Another is a contactless BLE token that combines secure storage and tokenized release of fingerprint credentials.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] In the USB mode of operation sign-off requires care for the token while mechanically coupled to the USB plug.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The advantage with the Bluetooth mode of operation is the option of combining sign-off with distance metrics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Respective products are in preparation, following the concepts of electronic leash.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Near-field communication (NFC) tokens combined with a Bluetooth token may operate in several modes, thus working in both a connected and a disconnected state.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] NFC authentication works when closer than 1 foot (0.3 meters).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The NFC protocol bridges short distances to the reader while the Bluetooth connection serves for data provision with the token to enable authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Also when the Bluetooth link is not connected, the token may serve the locally stored authentication information in coarse positioning to the NFC reader and relieves from exact positioning to a connector.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Some types of single sign-on (SSO) solutions, like enterprise single sign-on, use the token to store software that allows for seamless authentication and password filling.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] As the passwords are stored on the token, users need not remember their passwords and therefore can select more secure passwords, or have more secure passwords assigned.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Usually most tokens store a cryptographic hash of the password so that if the token is compromised, the password is still protected.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Programmable tokens are marketed as "drop-in" replacement of mobile applications such as Google Authenticator (miniOTP).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] They can be used as mobile app replacement, as well as in parallel as a backup.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The simplest vulnerability with any password container is theft or loss of the device.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] The chances of this happening, or happening unaware, can be reduced with physical security measures such as locks, electronic leash, or body sensor and alarm.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Stolen tokens can be made useless by using two factor authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Commonly, in order to authenticate, a personal identification number (PIN) must be entered along with the information provided by the token the same time as the output of the token.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Any system which allows users to authenticate via an untrusted network (such as the Internet) is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] In this type of attack, an attacker acts as the "go-between" of the user and the legitimate system, soliciting the token output from the legitimate user and then supplying it to the authentication system themselves.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Since the token value is mathematically correct, the authentication succeeds and the fraudster is granted access.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] In 2006, Citibank was the victim of an attack when its hardware-token-equipped business users became the victims of a large Ukrainian-based man-in-the-middle phishing operation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] In 2012, the Prosecco research team at INRIA Paris-Rocquencourt developed an efficient method of extracting the secret key from several PKCS #11 cryptographic devices.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] These findings were documented in INRIA Technical Report RR-7944, ID hal-00691958, and published at CRYPTO 2012.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Trusted as a regular hand-written signature, the digital signature must be made with a private key known only to the person authorized to make the signature.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Tokens that allow secure on-board generation and storage of private keys enable secure digital signatures, and can also be used for user authentication, as the private key also serves as a proof of the user's identity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] For tokens to identify the user, all tokens must have some kind of number that is unique.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Not all approaches fully qualify as digital signatures according to some national laws.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/security-token] Tokens with no on-board keyboard or another user interface cannot be used in some signing scenarios, such as confirming a bank transaction based on the bank account number that the funds are to be transferred to.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A **smart card** (**SC**), **chip card**, or **integrated circuit card** (**ICC** or **IC card**), is a card used to control access to a resource.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] It is typically a plastic credit card-sized card with an embedded integrated circuit (IC) chip.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Many smart cards include a pattern of metal contacts to electrically connect to the internal chip.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Others are contactless, and some are both.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Smart cards can provide personal identification, authentication, data storage, and application processing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Applications include identification, financial, public transit, computer security, schools, and healthcare.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Smart cards may provide strong security authentication for single sign-on (SSO) within organizations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Numerous nations have deployed smart cards throughout their populations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The universal integrated circuit card (UICC) for mobile phones, installed as pluggable SIM card or embedded eSIM, is also a type of smart card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As of 2015, 10.5 billion smart card IC chips are manufactured annually, including 5.44 billion SIM card IC chips.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The basis for the smart card is the silicon integrated circuit (IC) chip.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] It was invented by Robert Noyce at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1959.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The invention of the silicon integrated circuit led to the idea of incorporating it onto a plastic card in the late 1960s.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The idea of incorporating an integrated circuit chip onto a plastic card was first introduced by the German engineer Helmut Gröttrup.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In February 1967, Gröttrup filed the patents DE1574074 and DE1574075 in West Germany for a tamper-proof identification switch based on a semiconductor device and described contactless communication via inductive coupling.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Its primary use was intended to provide individual copy-protected keys for releasing the tapping process at unmanned gas stations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In September 1968, Gröttrup, together with Jürgen Dethloff as an investor, filed further patents for this identification switch, first in Austria and in 1969 as subsequent applications in the United States, Great Britain, West Germany and other countries.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Independently, Kunitaka Arimura of the Arimura Technology Institute in Japan developed a similar idea of incorporating an integrated circuit onto a plastic card, and filed a smart card patent in March 1970.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The following year, Paul Castrucci of IBM filed an American patent titled "Information Card" in May 1971.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 1974 Roland Moreno patented a secured memory card later dubbed the "smart card".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 1976, Jürgen Dethloff introduced the known element (called "the secret") to identify gate user as of USP 4105156.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 1977, Michel Ugon from Honeywell Bull invented the first microprocessor smart card with two chips: one microprocessor and one memory, and in 1978, he patented the self-programmable one-chip microcomputer (SPOM) that defines the necessary architecture to program the chip.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Three years later, Motorola used this patent in its "CP8".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] At that time, Bull had 1,200 patents related to smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2001, Bull sold its CP8 division together with its patents to Schlumberger, who subsequently combined its own internal smart card department and CP8 to create Axalto.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2006, Axalto and Gemplus, at the time the world's top two smart-card manufacturers, merged and became Gemalto.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2008, Dexa Systems spun off from Schlumberger and acquired Enterprise Security Services business, which included the smart-card solutions division responsible for deploying the first large-scale smart-card management systems based on public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first mass use of the cards was as a telephone card for payment in French payphones, starting in 1983.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] After the Télécarte, microchips were integrated into all French *Carte Bleue* debit cards in 1992.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Customers inserted the card into the merchant's point-of-sale (POS) terminal, then typed the personal identification number (PIN), before the transaction was accepted.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Only very limited transactions (such as paying small highway tolls) are processed without a PIN.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Smart-card-based "electronic purse" systems store funds on the card, so that readers do not need network connectivity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] They entered European service in the mid-1990s.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Private electronic purse systems have also been deployed such as the Marines corps (USMC) at Parris Island allowing small amount payments at the cafeteria.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Since the 1990s, smart cards have been the subscriber identity modules (SIMs) used in GSM mobile-phone equipment.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Mobile phones are widely used across the world, so smart cards have become very common.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Europay MasterCard Visa (EMV)-compliant cards and equipment are widespread with the deployment led by European countries.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The United States started later deploying the EMV technology in 2014, with the deployment still in progress in 2019.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Typically, a country's national payment association, in coordination with MasterCard International, Visa International, American Express and Japan Credit Bureau (JCB), jointly plan and implement EMV systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Historically, in 1993 several international payment companies agreed to develop smart-card specifications for debit and credit cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The original brands were MasterCard, Visa, and Europay.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first version of the EMV system was released in 1994.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 1998 the specifications became stable.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] EMVco's purpose is to assure the various financial institutions and retailers that the specifications retain backward compatibility with the 1998 version.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] EMVco upgraded the specifications in 2000 and 2004.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] EMV compliant cards were first accepted into Malaysia in 2005 and later into United States in 2014.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] MasterCard was the first company that was allowed to use the technology in the United States.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The United States has felt pushed to use the technology because of the increase in identity theft.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The credit card information stolen from Target in late 2013 was one of the largest indicators that American credit card information is not safe.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Target made the decision on 30 April 2014 that it would try to implement the smart chip technology to protect itself from future credit card identity theft.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Before 2014, the consensus in America was that there were enough security measures to avoid credit card theft and that the smart chip was not necessary.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The cost of the smart chip technology was significant, which was why most of the corporations did not want to pay for it in the United States.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The debate finally ended when Target sent out a notice stating unauthorized access to magnetic strips costing Target over 300 million dollars along with the increasing cost of online credit theft was enough for the United States to invest in the technology.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The adaptation of EMV's increased significantly in 2015 when the liability shifts occurred in October by the credit card companies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Use of "Contactless" smart cards in transport has also grown through the use of low cost chips NXP Mifare Ultralight and paper/card/PET rather than PVC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This has reduced media cost so it can be used for low cost tickets and short term transport passes (up to 1 year typically).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The cost is typically 10% that of a PVC smart card with larger memory.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] They are distributed through vending machines, ticket offices and agents.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Use of paper/PET is less harmful to the environment than traditional PVC cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Smart cards are also being introduced for identification and entitlement by regional, national, and international organizations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These uses include citizen cards, drivers’ licenses, and patient cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In Malaysia, the compulsory national ID MyKad enables eight applications and has 18 million users.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Contactless smart cards are part of ICAO biometric passports to enhance security for international travel.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards are smart cards that conform to the ISO/IEC 7810 standard and include components in addition to those found in traditional single chip smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards were invented by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud in 1999 when they designed a chip smart card with additional components, building upon the initial concept consisting of using audio frequencies to transmit data patented by Alain Bernard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first Complex Card prototype was developed collaboratively by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, who were working at AudioSmartCard at the time, and Henri Boccia and Philippe Patrice, who were working at Gemplus.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] It was ISO 7810-compliant and included a battery, a piezoelectric buzzer, a button, and delivered audio functions, all within a 0.84mm thickness card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Complex Card pilot, developed by AudioSmartCard, was launched in 2002 by Crédit Lyonnais, a French financial institution.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This pilot featured acoustic tones as a means of authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Although Complex Cards were developed since the inception of the smart card industry, they only reached maturity after 2010.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] While first generation Complex Cards were battery powered, the second generation is battery-free and receives power through the usual card connector and/or induction .
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Sound, generated by a buzzer, was the preferred means of communication for the first projects involving Complex Cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Later, with the progress of displays, visual communication is now present in almost all Complex Cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards support all communication protocols present on regular smart cards: contact, thanks to a contact pad as defined ISO/IEC 7816 standard, contactless following the ISO/IEC 14443 standard, and magstripe.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card can be used to compute a cryptographic value, such as a One-time password.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The One-Time Password is generated by a cryptoprocessor encapsulated in the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] To implement this function, the crypto processor must be initialized with a seed value, which enables the identification of the OTPs respective of each card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The hash of seed value has to be stored securely within the card to prevent unauthorized prediction of the generated OTPs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] One-Time Passwords generation is based either on incremental values (event based) or on a real time clock (time based).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Using clock-based One-Time Password generation requires the Complex Card to be equipped with a Real-time clock.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card with buttons can display the balance of one or multiple account(s) linked to the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Typically, either one button is used to display the balance in the case of a single account card or, in the case of a card linked to multiple accounts, a combination of buttons is used to select a specific account's balance.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] For additional security, features such as requiring the user to enter an identification or a security value such as a PIN can be added to a Complex Card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The latest generation of battery free, button free, Complex Cards can display a balance or other kind of information without requiring any input from the card holder.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The information is updated during the use of the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] For instance, in a transit card, key information such as the monetary value balance, the number of remaining trips or the expiry date of a transit pass can be displayed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card being deployed as a payment card can be equipped with capability to provide transaction security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Typically, online payments are made secure thanks to the Card Security Code (CSC), also known as card verification code (CVC2), or card verification value (CVV2).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The card security code (CSC) is a 3 or 4 digits number printed on a credit or debit card, used as a security feature for card-not-present (CNP) payment card transactions to reduce the incidence of fraud.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Card Security Code (CSC) is to be given to the merchant by the cardholder to complete a card-not-present transaction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The CSC is transmitted along with other transaction data and verified by the card issuer.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) prohibits the storage of the CSC by the merchant or any stakeholder in the payment chain.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Although designed to be a security feature, the static CSC is susceptible to fraud as it can easily be memorized by a shop attendant, who could then use it for fraudulent online transactions or sale on the dark web.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This vulnerability has led the industry to develop a Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC) that can be changed at certain time intervals, or after each contact or contactless EMV transaction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This Dynamic CSC brings significantly better security than a static CSC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first generation of Dynamic CSC cards, developed by NagraID Security required a battery, a quartz and Real Time Clock (RTC) embedded within the card to power the computation of a new Dynamic CSC, after expiration of the programmed period.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The second generation of Dynamic CSC cards, developed by Ellipse World, Inc., does not require any battery, quartz, or RTC to compute and display the new dynamic code.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Instead, the card obtains its power either through the usual card connector or by induction during every EMV transaction from the Point of Sales (POS) terminal or Automated Teller Machine (ATM) to compute a new DCSC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The advantage of the Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC) is that new information is transmitted with the payment transactions, thus making it useless for a potential fraudster to memorize or store it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A transaction with a Dynamic Card Security Code is carried out exactly the same way, with the same processes and use of parameters as a transaction with a static code in a card-not-present transaction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Upgrading to a DCSC allows cardholders and merchants to continue their payment habits and processes undisturbed.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards can be equipped with biometric sensors allowing for stronger user authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In the typical use case, fingerprint sensors are integrated into a payment card to bring a higher level of user authentication than a PIN.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] To implement user authentication using a fingerprint enabled smart card, the user has to authenticate himself/herself to the card by means of the fingerprint before starting a payment transaction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards can incorporate a wide variety of components.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The choice of components drives functionality, influences cost, power supply needs, and manufacturing complexity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Depending on Complex Card types, buttons have been added to allow an easy interaction between the user and the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] While separate keys have been used on prototypes in the early days, capacitive keyboards are the most popular solution now, thanks to technology developments by AudioSmartCard International SA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The interaction with a capacitive keyboard requires constant power, therefore a battery and a mechanical button are required to activate the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first Complex Cards were equipped with a buzzer that made it possible to broadcast sound.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This feature was generally used over the phone to send identification data such as an identifier and one-time passwords (OTPs).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Technologies used for sound transmission include DTMF (dual-tone multi-frequency signaling) or FSK (frequency-shift keying).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Displaying data is an essential part of Complex Card functionalities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Depending on the information that needs to be shown, displays can be digital or alphanumeric and of varying lengths.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Displays can be located either on the front or back of the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A front display is the most common solution for showing information such as a One-Time Password or an electronic purse balance.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A rear display is more often used for showing a Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] If a Complex smart Card is dedicated to making cryptographic computations (such as generating a one-time password) it may require a secure cryptoprocessor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards contain more components than traditional smart cards, their power consumption must be carefully monitored.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] First generation Complex Cards require a power supply even in standby mode.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As such, product designers generally included a battery in their design.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Incorporating a battery creates an additional burden in terms of complexity, cost, space and flexibility in an already dense design.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Including a battery in a Complex Card increases the complexity of the manufacturing process as a battery cannot be hot laminated.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Second generation Complex Cards feature a battery-free design.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These cards harvest the necessary power from external sources; for example when the card interacts in a contact or contactless fashion with a payment system or an NFC-enabled smartphone.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The use of a bistable display in the card design ensures that the screen remains legible even when the Complex Card is unconnected to the power source.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Card manufacturing methods are inherited from the smart card industry and from the electronics mounting industry.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards incorporate several components while having to remain within 0.8 mm thickness and be flexible, and to comply with the ISO/IEC 7810, ISO/IEC 7811 and ISO/IEC 7816 standards, renders their manufacture more complex than standard smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] One of the most popular manufacturing processes in the smart card industry is lamination.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This process involves laminating an inlay between two card faces.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The inlay contains the needed electronic components with an antenna printed on an inert support.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Typically battery-powered Complex Cards require a cold lamination manufacturing process.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This process impacts the manufacturing lead time and the whole cost of such a Complex Card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Second generation, battery-free Complex Cards can be manufactured by existing hot lamination process.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This automated process, inherited from traditional smart card manufacturing, enables the production of Complex Cards in large quantities while keeping costs under control, a necessity for the evolution from a niche to a mass market.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards bring more functionalities than standard smart cards and, due to their complexity, their personalization can take longer or require more inputs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Having Complex Cards that can be personalized by the same machines and the same processes as regular smart cards allows them to be integrated more easily in existing manufacturing chains and applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] First generation, battery-operated Complex Cards require specific recycling processes, mandated by different regulatory bodies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Additionally, keeping battery-operated Complex Cards in inventory for extended periods of time may reduce their performance due to battery ageing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Second-generation battery-free technology ensures operation during the entire lifetime of the card and eliminates self-discharge, providing extended shelf life, and is more eco-friendly.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Since the inception of smart cards, innovators have been trying to add extra features.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As technologies have matured and have been industrialized, several smart card industry players have been involved in Complex Cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Complex Card concept began in 1999 when Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, its inventors, first designed a smart card with additional components.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The first prototype was developed collaboratively by Cyril Lalo, who was the CEO of AudioSmartCard at the time, and Henri Boccia and Philippe Patrice, from Gemplus.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The prototype included a button and audio functions on a 0.84mm thick ISO 7810-compliant card .
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Since then, Complex Cards have been mass-deployed primarily by NagraID Security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard International SA was instrumental in developing the first Complex Card that included a battery, a piezoelectric buzzer, a button, and audio functions all on a 0.84mm thick, ISO 7810-compatible card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard was founded in 1993 and specialized in the development and marketing of acoustic tokens incorporating security features.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These acoustic tokens exchanged data in the form of sounds transmitted over a phone line.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 1999, AudioSmartCard transitioned to a new leadership under Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, who also became major shareholders.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] They made AudioSmartCard evolve towards the smart card world.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2003 Prosodie, a subsidiary of Capgemini, joined the shareholders of AudioSmartCard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard was renamed nCryptone, in 2004.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] CardLab Innovation, incorporated in 2006 in Herlev, Denmark, specializes in Complex Cards that include a switch, a biometric reader, an RFID jammer, and one or more magstripes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company works with manufacturing partners in China and Thailand and owns a card lamination factory in Thailand.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Coin was a US-based startup founded in 2012 by Kanishk Parashar.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] It developed a Complex Card capable of storing the data of several credit and debit cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The card prototype was equipped with a display and a button that enabled the user to switch between different cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2015, the original Coin card concept evolved into Coin 2.0 adding contactless communication to its original magstripe emulation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Coin was acquired by Fitbit in May 2016 and all Coin activities were discontinued in February 2017.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Ellipse World, Inc. was founded in 2017 by Cyril Lalo and Sébastien Pochic, both recognized experts in Complex Card technology.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Ellipse World, Inc. specializes in battery-free Complex Card technology.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Ellipse patented technologies enable smart card manufacturers to use their existing dual interface payment card manufacturing process and supply chain to build battery-free, second generation Complex Cards with display capabilities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Thanks to this ease of integration, smart card vendors are able to address banking, transit and prepaid cards markets.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] EMue Technologies, headquartered in Melbourne, Australia, designed and developed authentication solutions for the financial services industry from 2009 to 2015.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company's flagship product, developed in collaboration with Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, was the eMue Card, a Visa CodeSure credit card with an embedded keypad, a display and a microprocessor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Feitian Technologies, a China-based company created in 1998, provides cyber security products and solutions.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company offers security solutions based on smart cards as well as other authentication devices.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These include Complex Cards, that incorporate a display, a keypad or a fingerprint sensor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Fingerprint Cards AB (or Fingerprints) is a Swedish company specializing in biometric solutions.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company sells biometric sensors and has recently introduced payment cards incorporating a fingerprint sensor such as the Zwipe card, a biometric dual-interface payment card using an integrated sensor from Fingerprints.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Giesecke & Devrient, also known as G+D, is a German company headquartered in Munich that provides banknotes, security printing, smart cards and cash handling systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Its smart card portfolio includes display cards, OTP cards, as well as cards displaying a Dynamic CSC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Gemalto, a division of Thales Group, is a major player in the secure transaction industry.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company's Complex Card portfolio includes cards with a display or a fingerprint sensor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These cards may display an OTP or a Dynamic CSC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] IDEMIA is the product of the 2017 merger of Oberthur Technologies and Morpho.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The combined company has positioned itself as a global provider of financial cards, SIM cards, biometric devices as well as public and private identity solutions.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Due to Oberthur's acquisition of NagraID Security in 2014, Idemia's Complex Card offerings include the F.CODE biometric payment card that includes a fingerprint sensor, and its battery-powered Motion Code card that displays a Dynamic CSC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] IDEX Biometrics ASA, incorporated in Norway, specializes in fingerprint identification technologies for personal authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company offers fingerprint sensors and modules that are ready to be embedded into cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Founded in 2002, by Alan Finkelstein, Innovative Card Technologies developed and commercialized enhancements for the smart card market.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company acquired the display card assets of nCryptone in 2006.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Innovative Card Technologies has ceased its activities.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID, now known as NID, was a wholly owned subsidiary of the Kudelski Group until 2014.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] NID can trace its history with Complex Cards back to 2003 when it collaborated on development with nCryptone.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID was instrumental in developing the cold lamination process for Complex Cards manufacturing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID manufactures Complex Cards that can include a battery, buttons, displays or other electronic components.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID Security began in 2008 as a spinoff of Nagra ID to focus on Complex Card development and manufacturing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company was owned by Kudelski Group (50%), Cyril Lalo (25%) and Philippe Guillaud (25%).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] NagraID Security quickly became a leading player in the adoption of Complex Cards due, in large part, to its development of MotionCode cards that featured a small display to enable a Card Security Code (CVV2).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] NagraID Security was the first Complex Cards manufacturer to develop a mass market for payment display cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2014, NagraID Security was sold to Oberthur Technologies (now IDEMIA).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] nCryptone emerged in 2004 from the renaming of AudioSmartCard. nCryptone was headed by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud and developed technologies around authentication servers and devices.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] nCryptone display card assets were acquired by Innovative Card Technologies in 2006.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Oberthur Technologies, now IDEMIA, is one of the major players in the secure transactions industry.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] It acquired the business of NagraID Security in 2014.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Oberthur then merged with Morpho and the combined entity was renamed Idemia in 2017.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Set up in 2009, Plastc announced a single card that could digitally hold the data of up to 20 credit or debit cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company succeeded in raising US$9 million through preorders but failed to deliver any product.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Plastc was then acquired in 2017 by Edge Mobile Payments, a Santa Cruz-based Fintech company.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Plastc project continues as the Edge card, a dynamic payment card that consolidates several payment cards in one device.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The card is equipped with a battery and an ePaper screen and can store data from up to 50 credit, debit, loyalty and gift cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Stratos was created in 2012 in Ann Arbor, Michigan, USA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2015, Stratos developed the Stratos Bluetooth Connected Card, which was designed to integrate up to three credit and debit card in a single card format and featured a smartphone app used to manage the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Due to its Lithium ion thin film battery, the Stratos card was equipped with LEDs and communicated in contactless mode and in Bluetooth low Energy.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In 2017 Stratos was acquired by CardLab Innovation, a company headquartered in Herlev, Denmark.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] SWYP was the brand name of a card developed by Qvivr, a company incorporated in 2014 in Fremont, California.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] SWYP was introduced in 2015 and dubbed the world's first smart wallet.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] SWYP was a metal card with the ability to combine over 25 credit, debit, gift and loyalty cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The card worked in conjunction with a smartphone app used to manage the cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The Swyp card included a battery, a button and a matrix display that showed which card was in use.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The company registered users in its beta testing program, but the product never shipped on a commercial scale.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Qvivr raised US$5 million in January 2017 and went out of business in November 2017.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards have been adopted by numerous financial institutions worldwide.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] They may include different functionalities such as payment cards (credit, debit, prepaid), One-time password, mass-transit, and dynamic Card Security Code (CVV2).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Since April 2009, a Japanese company has manufactured reusable financial smart cards made from paper.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] As mentioned above, data on a smart card may be stored in a file system (FS).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In smart card file systems, the root directory is called the "master file" ("MF"), subdirectories are called "dedicated files" ("DF"), and ordinary files are called "elementary files" ("EF").
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The file system mentioned above is stored on an EEPROM (storage or memory) within the smartcard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In addition to the EEPROM, other components may be present, depending upon the kind of smartcard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] In cards with microprocessors, the microprocessor sits inline between the reader and the other components.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The operating system that runs on the microprocessor mediates the reader's access to those components to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Contact smart cards have a contact area of approximately 1 square centimetre (0.16 sq in), comprising several gold-plated contact pads.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] These pads provide electrical connectivity when inserted into a reader, which is used as a communications medium between the smart card and a host (e.g., a computer, a point of sale terminal) or a mobile telephone.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Cards do not contain batteries; power is supplied by the card reader.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Because the chips in financial cards are the same as those used in subscriber identity modules (SIMs) in mobile phones, programmed differently and embedded in a different piece of PVC, chip manufacturers are building to the more demanding GSM/3G standards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] So, for example, although the EMV standard allows a chip card to draw 50 mA from its terminal, cards are normally well below the telephone industry's 6 mA limit.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This allows smaller and cheaper financial card terminals.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Communication protocols for contact smart cards include T=0 (character-level transmission protocol, defined in ISO/IEC 7816-3) and T=1 (block-level transmission protocol, defined in ISO/IEC 7816-3).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] APDU transmission by a contactless interface is defined in ISO/IEC 14443-4.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Hybrid cards implement contactless and contact interfaces on a single card with unconnected chips including dedicated modules/storage and processing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Dual-interface cards implement contactless and contact interfaces on a single chip with some shared storage and processing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] An example is Porto's multi-application transport card, called Andante, which uses a chip with both contact and contactless (ISO/IEC 14443 Type B) interfaces.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Numerous payment cards worldwide are based on hybrid card technology allowing them to communicate in contactless as well as contact modes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] The CCID (Chip Card Interface Device) is a USB protocol that allows a smart card to be interfaced to a computer using a card reader which has a standard USB interface.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] This allows the smart card to be used as a security token for authentication and data encryption such as Bitlocker.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] A typical CCID is a USB dongle and may contain a SIM.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Different smart cards implement one or more reader-side protocols.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Common protocols here include CT-API and PC/SC.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Smartcard operating systems may provide application programming interfaces (APIs) so that developers can write programs ("applications") to run on the smartcard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p01] Some such APIs, such as Java Card, allow programs to be uploaded to the card without replacing the card's entire operating system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards serve as credit or ATM cards, fuel cards, mobile phone SIMs, authorization cards for pay television, household utility pre-payment cards, high-security identification and access badges, and public transport and public phone payment cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards may also be used as electronic wallets.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The smart card chip can be "loaded" with funds to pay parking meters, vending machines or merchants.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Cryptographic protocols protect the exchange of money between the smart card and the machine.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The holder of the card may use it even if not the owner.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Examples are Mondex (1993), Proton, Geldkarte, Chipknip and Moneo.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The German Geldkarte is also used to validate customer age at vending machines for cigarettes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Contactless (non-PIN) transactions cover a payment range of ~$5–50.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] There is an ISO/IEC 14443 PayPass implementation.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Some, but not all, PayPass implementations conform to EMV.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Non-EMV cards work like magnetic stripe cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The cards do not hold or maintain the account balance.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] All payment passes without a PIN, usually in off-line mode.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The security of such a transaction is no greater than with a magnetic stripe card transaction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] EMV cards can have either contact or contactless interfaces.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] They work as if they were a normal EMV card with a contact interface.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Via the contactless interface they work somewhat differently, in that the card commands enabled improved features such as lower power and shorter transaction times.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] EMV standards include provisions for contact and contactless communications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Typically modern payment cards are based on hybrid card technology and support both contact and contactless communication modes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The subscriber identity modules used in mobile-phone systems are reduced-size smart cards, using otherwise identical technologies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Sometimes they employ a public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The card stores an encrypted digital certificate issued from the PKI provider along with other relevant information.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Department of Defense (DoD) Common Access Card (CAC), and other cards used by other governments for their citizens.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] If they include biometric identification data, cards can provide superior two- or three-factor authentication.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are not always privacy-enhancing, because the subject may carry incriminating information on the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Contactless smart cards that can be read from within a wallet or even a garment simplify authentication; however, criminals may access data from these cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Cryptographic smart cards are often used for single sign-on.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Most advanced smart cards include specialized cryptographic hardware that uses algorithms such as RSA and Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Today's cryptographic smart cards generate key pairs on board, to avoid the risk from having more than one copy of the key (since by design there usually isn't a way to extract private keys from a smart card).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Such smart cards are mainly used for digital signatures and secure identification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The most common way to access cryptographic smart card functions on a computer is to use a vendor-provided PKCS#11 library.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] On Microsoft Windows the Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) API is also supported.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The most widely used cryptographic algorithms in smart cards (excluding the GSM so-called "crypto algorithm") are Triple DES and RSA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The key set is usually loaded (DES) or generated (RSA) on the card at the personalization stage.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Some of these smart cards are also made to support the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) standard for Personal Identity Verification, FIPS 201.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Turkey implemented the first smart card driver's license system in 1987.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Turkey had a high level of road accidents and decided to develop and use digital tachograph devices on heavy vehicles, instead of the existing mechanical ones, to reduce speed violations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Since 1987, the professional driver's licenses in Turkey have been issued as smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] A professional driver is required to insert his driver's license into a digital tachograph before starting to drive.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The tachograph unit records speed violations for each driver and gives a printed report.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The driving hours for each driver are also being monitored and reported.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In 1990 the European Union conducted a feasibility study through BEVAC Consulting Engineers, titled "Feasibility study with respect to a European electronic drivers license (based on a smart-card) on behalf of Directorate General VII".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In this study, chapter seven describes Turkey's experience.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Argentina's Mendoza province began using smart card driver's licenses in 1995.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Mendoza also had a high level of road accidents, driving offenses, and a poor record of recovering fines.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart licenses hold up-to-date records of driving offenses and unpaid fines.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] They also store personal information, license type and number, and a photograph.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Emergency medical information such as blood type, allergies, and biometrics (fingerprints) can be stored on the chip if the card holder wishes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The Argentina government anticipates that this system will help to collect more than $10 million per year in fines.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In 1999 Gujarat was the first Indian state to introduce a smart card license system.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] As of 2005, it has issued 5 million smart card driving licenses to its people.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In 2002, the Estonian government started to issue smart cards named ID Kaart as primary identification for citizens to replace the usual passport in domestic and EU use.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] As of 2010 about 1 million smart cards have been issued (total population is about 1.3 million) and they are widely used in internet banking, buying public transport tickets, authorization on various websites etc.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] By the start of 2009, the entire population of Belgium was issued eID cards that are used for identification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] These cards contain two certificates: one for authentication and one for signature.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] More and more services in Belgium use eID for authorization.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Spain started issuing national ID cards (DNI) in the form of smart cards in 2006 and gradually replaced all the older ones with smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The idea was that many or most bureaucratic acts could be done online but it was a failure because the Administration did not adapt and still mostly requires paper documents and personal presence.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] On 14 August 2012, the ID cards in Pakistan were replaced.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The Smart Card is a third generation chip-based identity document that is produced according to international standards and requirements.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The card has over 36 physical security features and has the latest encryption codes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] This smart card replaced the NICOP (the ID card for overseas Pakistani).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards may identify emergency responders and their skills.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Cards like these allow first responders to bypass organizational paperwork and focus more time on the emergency resolution.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] WidePoint Corporation, a smart card provider to FEMA, produces cards that contain additional personal information, such as medical records and skill sets.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In 2007, the Open Mobile Alliance (OMA) proposed a new standard defining V1.0 of the Smart Card Web Server (SCWS), an HTTP server embedded in a SIM card intended for a smartphone user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The non-profit trade association SIMalliance has been promoting the development and adoption of SCWS.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] SIMalliance states that SCWS offers end-users a familiar, OS-independent, browser-based interface to secure, personal SIM data.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] As of mid-2010, SIMalliance had not reported widespread industry acceptance of SCWS.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The OMA has been maintaining the standard, approving V1.1 of the standard in May 2009, and V1.2 was expected to be approved in October 2012.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are also used to identify user accounts on arcade machines.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards, used as transit passes, and integrated ticketing are used by many public transit operators.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Card users may also make small purchases using the cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Some operators offer points for usage, exchanged at retailers or for other benefits.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] However, these present a privacy risk because they allow the mass transit operator (and the government) to track an individual's movement.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In Finland, for example, the Data Protection Ombudsman prohibited the transport operator Helsinki Metropolitan Area Council (YTV) from collecting such information, despite YTV's argument that the card owner has the right to a list of trips paid with the card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Earlier, such information was used in the investigation of the Myyrmanni bombing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The UK's Department for Transport mandated smart cards to administer travel entitlements for elderly and disabled residents.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] These schemes let residents use the cards for more than just bus passes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] They can also be used for taxi and other concessionary transport.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] One example is the "Smartcare go" scheme provided by Ecebs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The UK systems use the ITSO Ltd specification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Other schemes in the UK include period travel passes, carnets of tickets or day passes and stored value which can be used to pay for journeys.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Other concessions for school pupils, students and job seekers are also supported.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] These are mostly based on the ITSO Ltd specification.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Many smart transport schemes include the use of low cost smart tickets for simple journeys, day passes and visitor passes.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] These smart tickets are made of paper or PET which is thinner than a PVC smart card e.g.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The smart tickets can be supplied pre-printed and over-printed or printed on demand.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In Sweden, as of 2018–19, the old SL Access smart card system has started to be phased out and replaced by smart phone apps.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The phone apps have less cost, at least for the transit operators who don't need any electronic equipment (the riders provide that).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The riders are able buy tickets anywhere and don't need to load money onto smart cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] New NFC smart cards are still in use for foreseeable future (as of 2024).
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In Japanese amusement arcades, contactless smart cards (usually referred to as "IC cards") are used by game manufacturers as a method for players to access in-game features (both online like Konami E-Amusement and Sega ALL.Net and offline) and as a memory support to save game progress.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Depending on a case by case scenario, the machines can use a game-specific card or a "universal" one usable on multiple machines from the same manufacturer/publisher.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Amongst the most widely used there are Banapassport by Bandai Namco, E-amusement pass by Konami, Aime by Sega and Nesica by Taito.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In 2018, in an effort to make arcade game IC cards more user friendly, Konami, Bandai Namco and Sega have agreed on a unified system of cards named *Amusement IC*.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Thanks to this agreement, the three companies are now using a unified card reader in their arcade cabinets, so that players are able to use their card, no matter if a Banapassport, an e-Amusement Pass or an Aime, with hardware and ID services of all three manufacturers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] A common logo for *Amusement IC* cards has been created, and this is now displayed on compatible cards from all three companies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] In January 2019, Taito announced that their Nesica card was also joining the *Amusement IC* agreement with the other three companies.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be used as a security token.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Mozilla's Firefox web browser can use smart cards to store certificates for use in secure web browsing.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Some disk encryption systems, such as VeraCrypt and Microsoft's BitLocker, can use smart cards to securely hold encryption keys, and also to add another layer of encryption to critical parts of the secured disk.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] GnuPG, the well known encryption suite, also supports storing keys in a smart card.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are also used for single sign-on to log on to computers.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are being provided to students at some schools and colleges.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are widely used to encrypt digital television streams.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] VideoGuard is a specific example of how smart card security worked.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The Malaysian government promotes MyKad as a single system for all smart-card applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] MyKad started as identity cards carried by all citizens and resident non-citizens.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Available applications now include identity, travel documents, drivers license, health information, an electronic wallet, ATM bank-card, public toll-road and transit payments, and public key encryption infrastructure.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The personal information inside the MYKAD card can be read using special APDU commands.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have been advertised as suitable for personal identification tasks, because they are engineered to be tamper resistant.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The chip usually implements some cryptographic algorithm.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] There are, however, several methods for recovering some of the algorithm's internal state.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Differential power analysis involves measuring the precise time and electric current required for certain encryption or decryption operations.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] This can deduce the on-chip private key used by public key algorithms such as RSA.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Some implementations of symmetric ciphers can be vulnerable to timing or power attacks as well.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be physically disassembled by using acid, abrasives, solvents, or some other technique to obtain unrestricted access to the on-board microprocessor.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Although such techniques may involve a risk of permanent damage to the chip, they permit much more detailed information (e.g., photomicrographs of encryption hardware) to be extracted.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The primary advantage of smart cards is their flexibility.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have multiple functions which simultaneously can be an ID, a credit card, a stored-value cash card, and a repository of personal information such as telephone numbers or medical history.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The card can be easily replaced if lost, and, the requirement for a PIN (or other form of security) provides additional security from unauthorised access to information by others.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] At the first attempt to use it illegally, the card would be deactivated by the card reader itself.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be electronic key rings, giving the bearer ability to access information and physical places without need for online connections.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] They are encryption devices, so that the user can encrypt and decrypt information without relying on unknown, and therefore potentially untrustworthy, appliances such as ATMs.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are very flexible in providing authentication at different level of the bearer and the counterpart.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Finally, with the information about the user that smart cards can provide to the other parties, they are useful devices for customizing products and services.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can also have multiple credentials for different applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] This encourages better security as the user only has to manage a single card which is not only less cognitive load and more convenient.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are easily produced and have vastly improved security allowing institutions to reduce their security spending.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be used in electronic commerce, over the Internet, though the business model used in current electronic commerce applications still cannot use the full feature set of the electronic medium.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] An advantage of smart cards for electronic commerce is their use customize services.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] For example, for the service supplier to deliver the customized service, the user may need to provide each supplier with their profile, a boring and time-consuming activity.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] A smart card can contain a non-encrypted profile of the bearer, so that the user can get customized services even without previous contacts with the supplier.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The plastic or paper card in which the chip is embedded is fairly flexible.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The larger the chip, the higher the probability that normal use could damage it.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Cards are often carried in wallets or pockets, a harsh environment for a chip and antenna in contactless cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] PVC cards can crack or break if bent/flexed excessively.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] However, for large banking systems, failure-management costs can be more than offset by fraud reduction.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The production, use and disposal of PVC plastic is known to be more harmful to the environment than other plastics.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Alternative materials including chlorine free plastics and paper are available for some smart applications.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] If the account holder's computer hosts malware, the smart card security model may be broken.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Malware can override the communication (both input via keyboard and output via application screen) between the user and the application.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Man-in-the-browser malware (e.g., the Trojan Silentbanker) could modify a transaction, unnoticed by the user.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Banks like Fortis and Belfius in Belgium and Rabobank ("random reader") in the Netherlands combine a smart card with an unconnected card reader to avoid this problem.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The customer enters a challenge received from the bank's website, a PIN and the transaction amount into the reader.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The reader returns an 8-digit signature.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] This signature is manually entered into the personal computer and verified by the bank, preventing point-of-sale-malware from changing the transaction amount.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have also been the targets of security attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] These attacks range from physical invasion of the card's electronics, to non-invasive attacks that exploit weaknesses in the card's software or hardware.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] The usual goal is to expose private encryption keys and then read and manipulate secure data such as funds.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Once an attacker develops a non-invasive attack for a particular smart card model, he or she is typically able to perform the attack on other cards of that model in seconds, often using equipment that can be disguised as a normal smart card reader.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] While manufacturers may develop new card models with additional information security, it may be costly or inconvenient for users to upgrade vulnerable systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Tamper-evident and audit features in a smart card system help manage the risks of compromised cards.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] Another problem is the lack of standards for functionality and security.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/smart-card-p02] To address this problem, the Berlin Group launched the ERIDANE Project to propose "a new functional and security framework for smart-card based Point of Interaction (POI) equipment".
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] TOTP is a cornerstone of the Initiative for Open Authentication (OATH) and is used in a number of two-factor authentication (2FA) systems.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] Through the collaboration of several OATH members, a TOTP draft was developed in order to create an industry-backed standard.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] It complements the event-based one-time standard HOTP, and it offers end user organizations and enterprises more choice in selecting technologies that best fit their application requirements and security guidelines.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] In 2008, OATH submitted a draft version of the specification to the IETF.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] This version incorporates all the feedback and commentary that the authors received from the technical community based on the prior versions submitted to the IETF.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] In May 2011, TOTP officially became RFC 6238.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] Both the authenticator and the authenticatee compute the TOTP value, then the authenticator checks whether the TOTP value supplied by the authenticatee matches the locally generated TOTP value.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] Some authenticators allow values that should have been generated before or after the current time in order to account for slight clock skews, network latency and user delays.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] Some implementations of TOTP for smartphones allow users to scan QR codes to add HOTP and TOTP tokens to their authenticator apps.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] TOTP `otpauth://` URIs begin with `otpauth://totp/` and must contain a label and secret.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] The label is encoded as part of the path, while the secret is encoded as query parameters.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] The URI may optionally contain other fields, such as the number of digits (which defaults to 6), the algorithm used (which defaults to SHA1), the period (which defaults to 30 seconds), and the issuer name.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] For example, the URI `otpauth://totp/Wikipedian?secret=JBSWY3DPFQQHO33SNRSCC` represents a TOTP token labeled "Wikipedian" with the secret `Hello, world!` encoded as ASCII.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] Unlike passwords, TOTP codes are only valid for a limited time.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] However, users must enter TOTP codes into an authentication page, which creates the potential for phishing attacks.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] However, due to the short window in which TOTP codes are valid, attackers must proxy the credentials in real time.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] TOTP credentials are also based on a shared secret known to both the client and the server, creating multiple locations from which a secret can be stolen.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] An attacker with access to this shared secret could generate new, valid TOTP codes at will.
[src:multi-factor-authentication/time-based-one-time-password] This can be a particular problem if the attacker breaches a large authentication database.
